{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0181YTeiFh6pBbc9WYuTJnuY","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! I've successfully extracted the full content of the Methodology sheet from the Excel file. Here's what I found:\n\n## Methodology Sheet Structure\n\n**Sheet Range:** A1:B28\n\n**Full Content by Cell:**\n\n| Cell | Content |\n|------|---------|\n| A1 | \"Please provide a brief explanation for how you approached working through this.\\r\\r\\n(what was your methodology, prompt(s), tools, etc)\" |\n| A3 | APPROACH: |\n| A4 | Structured the analysis end to end across 16 sequential steps, from workbook inspection through to executive memo generation. |\n| A5 | Reviewed the vendor dataset in full: loaded all 385 vendor records, calculated total spend, and mapped spend distribution across tiers. |\n| A6 | Identified workbook structure and template constraints upfront — reviewed all sheets, cell-level write rules, allowed department values, and the CEO/CFO memo format requirement (max 1 page + Google Doc link). |\n| A7 | Sequenced the analysis logically: inspection → spend concentration → vendor classification → service overlap → strategic scoring → opportunity sizing → recommendations → documentation. |\n| A9 | METHODOLOGY: |\n| A10 | Data review: vendor spend data sourced directly from the workbook; total spend and concentration across the vendor population analysed. |\n| A11 | Spend concentration analysis: top 10 vendors ranked by spend; long-tail vendors below $50K identified as rationalisation candidates. |\n| A12 | Vendor categorisation: service categories and departments assigned to all 385 vendors using domain knowledge and vendor naming conventions. |\n| A13 | Service overlap identification: duplicate service categories detected across vendors; consolidation candidates flagged within the same department and function. |\n| A14 | Cost optimisation framework: Terminate / Consolidate / Optimize decision rules applied per vendor based on spend level, strategic value, and overlap assessment. |\n| A15 | Opportunity prioritisation: top 3 opportunities selected by highest estimated annual savings and feasibility; pre-sized with effort and risk ratings. |\n| A17 | PROMPTS: |\n| A18 | A 16-step structured prompt workflow was designed and executed sequentially via Claude Code CLI. |\n| A19 | Each step had a single clearly scoped analytical task: inspect, classify, score, identify, validate, or document. |\n| A20 | Key prompts covered: workbook inspection, vendor classification, duplicate detection, strategic scoring, opportunity identification, methodology documentation, and executive memo generation. |\n| A21 | All prompts enforced strict output format rules: allowed departments, recommendation values, cell-level write constraints, and sheet-specific formatting requirements. |\n| A22 | Prompts were passed to Claude Code CLI via stdin pipe in non-interactive mode using printf. |\n| A24 | TOOLS: |\n| A25 | Claude Code CLI (Anthropic): AI reasoning and analytical tasks across all 16 steps. |\n| A26 | Node.js with xlsx (SheetJS) library: Excel workbook read and write operations. |\n| A27 | Python with openpyxl: post-pipeline formatting restoration from original template. |\n| A28 | Bash orchestration script: step sequencing, checkpoint and resume logic, log capture. |\n\n**Key Information:**\n- **Cell A1** contains the template instruction prompt asking for methodology explanation\n- The sheet documents a comprehensive 16-step analytical workflow covering vendor spend analysis\n- The methodology emphasizes structured analysis from inspection through executive memo generation\n- Tools used: Claude Code CLI, Node.js/xlsx, Python/openpyxl, and Bash orchestration\n- Column B appears to be empty (no values extracted)"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: acf916e547a4d0d0a (use SendMessage with to: 'acf916e547a4d0d0a' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 15421\ntool_uses: 1\nduratio